<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="basionym">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Basionym.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Agaricaceae" genus="Micromphale" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Micromphale subsp. sect." order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="section" section="Perforantia" species="glabrosipes" subSpecies="sect.">Micromphale sect. Perforantia</taxonomicName>
Singer. 1948. Sydowia 2: 32.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
1) Pileipellis, pileus and lamellar tramae and stipe medullary hyphae embedded in slime matrix; 2) pileipellis either: a) a layer of repent, encrusted hyphae, conspicuously clamped, usually with thickened walls (through gelatinization) and embedded in a slime matrix; or b) well-developed 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rameales</emphasis>
-structure; 3) cheilocystidia often absent, when present either clavate to utriform or 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">siccus</emphasis>
-type broom cell-like; 4) stipes usually less than 1 mm broad but often up to 40 mm long; ratio of pileus breadth to stipe length often large (see 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. pinophilus" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="pinophilus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. pinophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); 5) stipe usually vestured (but see 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. glabrosipes" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="glabrosipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. glabrosipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), usually appearing minutely barbed (30
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
); 6) lower stipe of dark, somber color, from dark sooty brown to virtually black; 6) rhizomorphs almost always present, always black, from &lt;2-40 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2-0.7 mm, branched or unbranched; 7) basidiospores without significant dimension differences; 8) species apparently more or less host-specific, fruiting on dead conifer needles or rotting deciduous leafy debris; 9) pleurocystidia consistently present, fusiform, varying somewhat in distal morphology; 10) clamp connections ubiquitous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Commentary.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Antonín">Antonin</normalizedToken>
and Noordeloos (1997) recognized 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus subsp. subsect." order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="subSection" section="Vestipedes" species="glabrosipes" subSection="Impudicae" subSpecies="subsect.">Gymnopus sect. Vestipedes subsect. Impudicae</taxonomicName>
, including 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. perforans" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="perforans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. perforans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based, it would seem on the fetid odor of basidiomata of the included taxa. Later (
<bibRefCitation author="Antonin, V" journalOrPublisher="IHV-Verlag, Berlin" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" refId="B4" refString="Antonin, V, Noordeloos, ME, 2010. A monograph of Marasmioid and Collybioid fungi in Europe. IHV-Verlag, Berlin" title="A monograph of Marasmioid and Collybioid fungi in Europe." year="2010">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Antonín">Antonin</normalizedToken>
and Noordeloos 2010
</bibRefCitation>
), subsect. 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subSection" subSection="Impudicae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Impudicae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was accepted at section rank, but basically included the same taxa as before. 
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson, AW" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="667 - 679" publicationUrl="10.3852/mycologia.97.3.667" refId="B41" refString="Wilson, AW, Desjardin, DE, 2005. Phylogenetic relationships in the gymnopoid and marasmioid fungi (Basidiomycetes, euagarics clade). Mycologia 97: 667 - 679, DOI: 10.3852/mycologia.97.3.667" title="Phylogenetic relationships in the gymnopoid and marasmioid fungi (Basidiomycetes, euagarics clade)." url="10.3852/mycologia.97.3.667" volume="97" year="2005">Wilson and Desjardin (2005)</bibRefCitation>
indicated that 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. perforans" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="perforans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. perforans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
formed its own clade sister to that of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. (Micromphale) foetidum" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="foetidum" subGenus="Micromphale">G. (Micromphale) foetidum</taxonomicName>
and other mainstream odious 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus" order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Gymnopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa. Based on the present study, the original 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Agaricaceae" genus="Micromphale" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Micromphale subsp. sect." order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="section" section="Perforantia" species="foetidum" subSpecies="sect.">Micromphale sect. Perforantia</taxonomicName>
is found to be more closely related to the 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus (Marasmius) androsaceus" order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="androsaceus" subGenus="Marasmius">Gymnopus (Marasmius) androsaceus</taxonomicName>
complex, not inclusive of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. foetidum" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="foetidum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. foetidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus subsp. sect." order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="section" section="Impudicae" species="foetidum" subSpecies="sect.">Gymnopus sect. Impudicae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
